==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*skrīþan'', from Indo-European ''*(s)kreit-, *(s)ker-'' ‘twist, turn, bend’.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon ''scrîðan'' (Dutch ''[[schrijden]]''), Old High German ''scrîtan'' (German ''[[schreiten]]''), Old Norse ''skríða'' ‘creep, glide’ (Swedish ''[[skrida]]'').  The Indo-European root also gave Latin ''[[crisare]]'' and Middle Irish ''crith'' (Breton ''[[skrija]]'' ‘tremble with fear’).

